(c) The so-called epistolacy uscos tlrc tenses is the com· monest peculiarity in the use of tenses to be found in the Letters. The writer of the letter imagines himself in the place of the recipient, and therefore usesa tense of past time in speaking of an event which was exactly or approxi- mately contemporaneous with the writijng of the letter. This usage-is most frequent with verbs indicating the writ- ing of a letter, or the sending of a letter or messenger,⁴ as egotibi aliquid de meis scriptis mittam: crilcil crat absoluti (Art. 1. 16. 18); quaemihi cernebant in merstem, qrcacad tc pertinere arbitrabar, qued in Ciliciam proficiscebar, existimavi me ad ‘tc oportere scribere (Fam. 2. 18. 3).
